article.description: Harvey Hale scored 17 points to help Wake Forest rout Fairfield 85-60 Friday night in its first game since Skip Prosser's death.
article.headline: Hale, Johnson lead Wake Forest to rout of Fairfield
article.linkText: Wake Forest raises banner to Prosser, then wins
article.story: WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) -- Dino Gaudio gave Skip Prosser's teary-eyed mother a pregame hug, nervously hoping to honor his late best friend with a victory. Then he went out and coached Wake Forest to exactly the kind of season-opening victory Prosser certainly would have been proud of. Harvey Hale and freshman James Johnson each scored 17 points to help the Demon Deacons rout Fairfield 85-60 Friday night in their first game since Prosser's death and in Gaudio's debut as his replacement. "You wanted to win so bad for him, it's almost a relief to me," Gaudio said. "It almost feels like, 'Thank goodness, we did it.' ... I tried not to put any pressure on the kids, but I'll be honest with you -- I felt a lot of pressure going into this game. Just me personally, not from anybody else, but for my buddy." Nearly everybody contributed for Wake Forest, which unveiled a banner bearing Prosser's likeness and then turned in exactly the kind of determined, disciplined play that he valued and that Gaudio vowed to maintain in Winston-Salem. "There's a banner now in the (arena), so we know especially every home game, he's watching us and he's still coaching us," forward L.D. Williams said. "We know day in and day out, when we go on and off the court, Coach Prosser's in heaven, looking down upon us, telling Coach Gaudio to get those guys to rebound better." Hale made 5-of-6 3-pointers and scored 14 points in the second half. Johnson added 10 rebounds, Williams had 12 points and Jamie Skeen scored 10 points for the Demon Deacons (1-0). Wake Forest never trailed, forced 23 turnovers, scored 33 points off those miscues and used an 11-0 run early in the second half to build a 26-point lead. "It's mission started, not mission accomplished," Gaudio said of the defensive improvement. After Chas McFarland's free throw pushed the Wake Forest lead to 57-31 with 16:20 left, Fairfield didn't get closer than 16. Mike Evanonvich scored 20 points and was 6-of-7 from 3-point range for the Stags (0-1). "I believe in miracles, and the miracle wasn't happening tonight," Fairfield coach Ed Cooley said. It was a night for Wake Forest to remember Prosser, who died July 26 of an apparent heart attack at age 56. The banner that bears his likeness hung from the rafters behind the team's bench, and he received an 80-second standing ovation from the crowd, including the tie-dyed "Screaming Demons" student section he helped create. Then the Demon Deacons showed the kind of promise that had Prosser so excited about the program's future -- and two members of his final recruiting class showed why they were considered such hot prospects. Shortly after slashing across the lane and flicking in a layup with his left hand, freshman Jeff Teague stole the ball from Devin Johnson and drove downcourt before delivering a behind-the-back bounce pass to James Johnson, whose dunk capped a 17-2 run that made it 40-19 with about 3 minutes before the break. "I thought he was going to throw it off the glass," James Johnson said, laughing. "Teague doesn't have any fear. ... Coach doesn't like it, but he completes it." Wake Forest shot nearly 56 percent during a dominant first half in which the Demon Deacons led by 21. Ish Smith's 3-pointer from the key in the final seconds gave Wake Forest a 45-25 lead. Fairfield made its first visit to Winston-Salem since the Stags' most recent appearance in the NCAA tournament. They were a No. 16 seed in 1997 but gave top-seeded North Carolina fits before falling 82-74.
